# Identify outliers in SALE.PRICE using the IQR method
Q1 <- quantile(data_boro$SALE.PRICE, 0.25, na.rm = TRUE)
Q3 <- quantile(data_boro$SALE.PRICE, 0.75, na.rm = TRUE)
IQR_val <- Q3 - Q1
lower_bound <- Q1 - 1.5 * IQR_val
upper_bound <- Q3 + 1.5 * IQR_val

outliers <- data_boro %>%
  filter(SALE.PRICE < lower_bound | SALE.PRICE > upper_bound)

cat("Number of outlier observations for Sale Price:", nrow(outliers), "\n")

Based on the EDA results, the following steps were taken and observed:

  1. The dataset was first filtered to include only the data points for the selected borough. The SALE.PRICE column was then cleaned to remove any values at 10 or below, and the GROSS.SQUARE.FEET and LAND.SQUARE.FEET columns underwent numeric conversion and removal of NA values, ensuring accuracy in subsequent analyses.

  2. Summary statistics and the structure of the filtered dataset were examined. This provided an initial understanding of the central tendencies, spread, and potential anomalies in the data.

  3. A histogram of the SALE.PRICE values was generated. This plot revealed the overall frequency distribution of home sale prices, highlighting where most transactions occurred and indicating any skewness in the data.

  4. A boxplot of the SALE.PRICE was also created to provide a visual representation of the distribution and to clearly identify potential outlier values. By applying the IQR method, the boundaries for typical sale prices were determined, and observations that fell outside of these bounds were marked as outliers.

  5. Additional plots, including scatter plots and a correlation matrix (using methods like corrplot), were produced. These visuals helped explore relationships between SALE.PRICE and other quantitative variables such as GROSS.SQUARE.FEET, lending insight into how different property attributes might influence the sale price.

This comprehensive exploratory analysis not only identified key trends within the dataset but also ensured that the subsequent modeling steps would be built on a well-understood and appropriately prepared dataset.

I began by converting TOTAL.UNITS and YEAR.BUILT to numeric and filtering out any rows that contained NA values for these crucial variables, ensuring clean numeric inputs. Next, I converted BOTH BUILDING.CLASS.AT.TIME.OF.SALE and TAX.CLASS.AT.TIME.OF.SALE into factors to properly account for their categorical nature in the model. I then tested multiple regression models, initially including LAND.SQUARE.FEET and YEAR.BUILT, but dropped them after finding them statistically insignificant (and TAX.CLASS.AT.TIME.OF.SALE due to collinearity). The simplified model (with GROSS.SQUARE.FEET, TOTAL.UNITS, and BUILDING.CLASS.AT.TIME.OF.SALE) achieved an R² of around 0.5032, which is comparable to the initial model’s performance but with fewer variables.

# k-NN
train_knn <- train_data %>% select(SALE.PRICE, GROSS.SQUARE.FEET)
test_knn <- test_data %>% select(SALE.PRICE, GROSS.SQUARE.FEET)

normalize <- function(x) {
  return((x - min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x)))
}

train_knn_norm <- as.data.frame(lapply(train_knn, normalize))
test_knn_norm <- as.data.frame(lapply(test_knn, normalize))

train_labels <- train_data$NEIGHBORHOOD
test_labels <- test_data$NEIGHBORHOOD

knn_pred <- knn(train = train_knn_norm,
                test = test_knn_norm,
                cl = train_labels,
                k = 5)

cat("=====kNN Results (k=5)=====\n")
## =====kNN Results (k=5)=====
confusionMatrix(knn_pred, test_labels)

The Naïve Bayes classifier yielded very low overall accuracy (around 4.7%) and poor sensitivity for most classes, suggesting that it struggles to distinguish among the diverse neighborhood categories based solely on the quantitative predictors. In contrast, the k-nearest neighbors (k-NN) classifier with k = 5 improved performance, achieving an accuracy of approximately 18.7% and slightly better sensitivity in some classes, though it still showed significant class imbalance. The Random Forest model outperformed both other approaches with an accuracy near 33.7% and a Kappa value of about 0.30, indicating a moderate level of agreement beyond chance; its ensemble approach appears better at capturing complex, nonlinear relationships in the data. Despite this improvement, all models displayed variability in sensitivity and specificity across different neighborhoods, which may be attributed to the high number of neighborhood levels and class imbalances. Overall, while the Random Forest classifier offers the best performance among the three methods, there remains room for further model refinement, such as grouping or rebalancing neighborhood categories, to achieve more consistent classification results.

I applied my best-performing model from 1.c, incorporating NEIGHBORHOOD, GROSS.SQUARE.FEET, TOTAL.UNITS, and BUILDING.CLASS.AT.TIME.OF.SALE, to the new borough’s dataset and obtained an R² of 0.51. The predicted vs. actual plot indicates a moderately strong linear relationship, but residuals remain sizeable, especially at higher sale prices. This suggests that while the model captures some fundamental trends, distinct neighborhood patterns and property attributes in the new borough introduce additional variance. Overall, the model generalizes just as well but is still limited by differences in local real-estate dynamics that were not capture in the original training borough.

# k-NN
train_knn <- train_data %>% select(SALE.PRICE, GROSS.SQUARE.FEET)
test_knn <- test_data %>% select(SALE.PRICE, GROSS.SQUARE.FEET)

normalize <- function(x) {
  return((x - min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x)))
}

train_knn_norm <- as.data.frame(lapply(train_knn, normalize))
test_knn_norm <- as.data.frame(lapply(test_knn, normalize))

train_labels <- train_data$NEIGHBORHOOD
test_labels <- test_data$NEIGHBORHOOD

knn_pred <- knn(train = train_knn_norm,
                test = test_knn_norm,
                cl = train_labels,
                k = 5)

cat("=====kNN Results (k=5)=====\n")
## =====kNN Results (k=5)=====
confusionMatrix(knn_pred, test_labels)

Based on my results, the Naïve Bayes and k-NN classifiers performed similarly across both datasets, with overall accuracies around 4–5% and approximately 18–19%, respectively. However, while the Random Forest model yielded a robust accuracy of about 33.7% (with a Kappa value of ~0.30) on the original borough dataset, its performance dropped considerably to roughly 15.9% (with a Kappa of ~0.12) on the new dataset. This discrepancy indicates that although the simpler models generalize consistently, the Random Forest model—which appears to capture complex, nonlinear patterns in the original data—may be overfitted to that specific borough’s characteristics. The reduced performance on the new dataset suggests there are differences in the underlying distribution of predictors (such as property size, total units, or building class) or neighborhood compositions that the Random Forest model did not fully capture. Overall, this comparison demonstrates that while some aspects of the model generalize well, further refinement or adjustment (e.g., through rebalancing or grouping neighborhood categories) may be necessary for the Random Forest classifier to perform robustly across different boroughs.

One key observation was that the new borough dataset on “2” contained a substaintal number of missing values and exhibited considerable variation in property attributes, which likely contributed to the models’ reduced performance. Additionally I noted that the large number of neighborhood categories introduced class imbalance, diminishing confidence in the classification metrics and underscoring the need for further data cleaning and potentially grouping neighborhoods to achieve more stable results.

Overall, the study shows that while linear models capture the primary drivers of sale price—such as gross square footage and total units—they still leave considerable unexplained variation, particularly in capturing the finer nuances across different neighborhoods. The Random Forest model, although generally performing better than simpler methods like Naïve Bayes and k-NN, still struggles with class imbalances and the high number of neighborhood categories. Regression and classification results indicate that issues with data quality, such as missing values and skewed distributions, combined with the inherent complexity of multiple building classes and neighborhoods, limit the reliability of the models. The notable drop in accuracy when applying the models to the second borough dataset suggests that the models do not generalize seamlessly beyond the training context, hinting at potential overfitting or unmodeled variations in local housing dynamics. To improve the results, future work could focus on grouping or rebalancing neighborhood categories, refining model parameters, or incorporating additional predictors (for example, building age or location-based scores) to more effectively capture the unique patterns present in each borough.
